er (North-West, North, North-East, Artibonite, Center, Grand Anse, Nippes, and South).","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":611,"renderedHeight":436,"naturalWidth":611,"naturalHeight":436,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 584 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":41082},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/TemplatePackage/images/icon_out.png","alt":"External Web Site Icon","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":10,"renderedHeight":10,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"GOOD","altReason":"present, no red flags","bytes":232},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/figures/m5930a1f2.gif","alt":"The figure shows the number and percentage of most frequently reported conditions, by epicenter proximity and surveillance week from January 25-April 24, 2010 in Haiti from the National Sentinel Site Surveillance System, Haiti. The two departments nearest the epicenter accounted for 53.6% (22,717) of the reported conditions. The three most frequently reported conditions in the departments nearest the epicenter were ARI 4,027 (17.7%); suspected malaria, 2,437 (10.7%); and fever of unknown cause, 2,238 (9.9%). Total injuries accounted for 2,084 (9.2%) of the reported conditions. In the eight departments further from the epicenter, among the 19,644 conditions reported, the three most frequently reported were injuries, 2,977 (15.2%); ARI, 2,858 (14.5%); and watery diarrhea, 2,059 (10.5%).","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":638,"renderedHeight":730,"naturalWidth":638,"naturalHeight":730,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 795 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":93718},{"src":"h